must also be preserved where applicable.

Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or without
modification, are permitted provided that the following conditions are met:

1. Redistributions of source code must retain the above copyright notice,
   this list of conditions, the following disclaimer, any existing ThinkJEPA
   attribution notices, and the original repository link:
   https://github.com/Hai-chao-Zhang/ThinkJEPA

2. Redistributions in binary form must reproduce the above copyright notice,
   this list of conditions, the following disclaimer, any existing ThinkJEPA
   attribution notices, and the original repository link:
   https://github.com/Hai-chao-Zhang/ThinkJEPA
   in the documentation and/or other materials provided with the distribution.

3. Neither the name of Northeastern University, NEU SMILE LAB, nor the names
   of the authors or contributors may be used to endorse or promote products
   derived from this software without specific prior written permission.

4. Any public redistribution of this software, in whole or in part, with or
   without modification, including within another open-source or closed-source
   repository, package, toolkit, benchmark, service, product, model release,
   or documentation set, must include a visible attribution notice in a
   user-facing location such as a top-level README, NOTICE file,
   documentation page, about page, release page, package metadata page, or
   equivalent materials.

   The attribution notice must include, at minimum:
   (a) the project name: "ThinkJEPA";
   (b) a statement that the redistributed software includes or is derived from
       ThinkJEPA; and
   (c) the original repository link:
       https://github.com/Hai-chao-Zhang/ThinkJEPA

5. If a redistributed or derivative version modifies this software, the
   redistributor must clearly state that changes were made and must not
   misrepresent the modified version as the original ThinkJEPA project.

6. For any public academic publication, technical report, white paper,
   benchmark report, blog post, public documentation release, patent
   application, patent specification, public prior-art disclosure, or similar
   public material that materially uses, implements, evaluates, or builds upon
   this software or a derivative work thereof, the user must provide
   reasonable attribution to ThinkJEPA, to the extent permitted by the rules
   of the relevant venue, publisher, patent office, or jurisdiction.

   Such attribution must, where reasonably practicable and to the extent
   permitted by the applicable rules, include:
   (a) the name "ThinkJEPA";
   (b) citation to the associated academic work, where a citation format is
       applicable; and
   (c) the original repository link:
       https://github.com/Hai-chao-Zhang/ThinkJEPA

   Where formal academic citation style is not applicable, this condition may
   be satisfied by including the above attribution in an acknowledgments,
   references, implementation details, prior-art, specification, notice, or
   equivalent section.

7. Public derivative repositories, packages, toolkits, services, or products
   that include or build upon ThinkJEPA should preserve any applicable
   third-party license files and notices shipped with this repository,
   including original upstream repository references where those notices
   require or recommend them.

Compliant attribution example:

  "This software includes or is derived from ThinkJEPA, originally developed
  at Northeastern University, NEU SMILE LAB by Haichao Zhang and Yun Raymond
  Fu. Original source: https://github.com/Hai-chao-Zhang/ThinkJEPA"

Compliant modified-version example:

  "Modified from ThinkJEPA (LicenseRef-ThinkJEPA-Attribution).
  Changes were made to the original software. Original source:
  https://github.com/Hai-chao-Zhang/ThinkJEPA"

